    # SNCA (α-Synuclein) — Expert Analysis
    **Biological function.** SNCA encodes α-synuclein, a 140-aa intrinsically disordered presynaptic protein concentrated at nerve terminals, where it regulates synaptic vesicle trafficking, SNARE complex assembly, and dopamine release. Its N-terminal amphipathic repeats (residues 1–60) drive membrane binding and adopt α-helical conformation on lipid surfaces; the central NAC domain (61–95) is the aggregation-prone core; the acidic C-terminus modulates chaperone interaction and metal binding. Under pathological conditions, α-synuclein misfolds into β-sheet–rich oligomers and fibrils that template prion-like spread along anatomically connected circuits — the molecular substrate of Lewy pathology.
    **Key variants and structural genetics.** Six missense mutations cause autosomal-dominant Parkinson's disease with near-complete penetrance: **A53T** (original Contursi kindred, accelerates fibrillization), **A30P** (impairs membrane binding, favors cytosolic oligomers), **E46K** (enhances lipid binding, causes DLB-like phenotype), **H50Q**, **G51D** (severe early-onset, MSA-like), and **A53E**. Equally important are **genomic multiplications** — duplications produce typical late-onset PD; triplications produce aggressive early-onset PD with dementia — establishing a strict gene-dosage relationship. The promoter **REP1** dinucleotide repeat and 3′ UTR SNPs (rs356182) are among the strongest common-variant GWAS hits in sporadic PD.
    **Disease associations.** SNCA is the defining molecule of the **synucleinopathies**: Parkinson's disease, dementia with Lewy bodies, and multiple system atrophy (where aggregates localize to oligodendrocytes rather than neurons). The 137 kb locus harbors regulatory elements that drive expression-level differences linked to sporadic PD risk; even modest increases in wild-type α-synuclein are pathogenic. Seed amplification assays (RT-QuIC, PMCA) on CSF and skin now detect misfolded α-synuclein with >90% sensitivity/specificity and have entered the **MDS biological definition of PD** (SynNeurGe / Neuronal Synuclein Disease framework), shifting the field from clinical to molecular diagnosis.
    **Therapeutic landscape.** Multiple modalities target this gene directly: **ASOs** (BIIB101/ION464 for MSA, in trial), **siRNA**, anti-aggregation small molecules (anle138b, minzasolmin/UCB0599), and passive immunotherapies (prasinezumab, cinpanemab — both missed primary endpoints but signal subgroup effects). LRRK2 and GBA1 modulators act upstream of α-synuclein clearance. The dosage data argue that **lowering wild-type SNCA expression** is a rational strategy across sporadic PD, not just familial cases.
    **Experimental recommendations.** (1) For mechanism: use isogenic iPSC-derived midbrain dopaminergic neurons with **SNCA triplication corrected to diploid** as the cleanest dose-response model; A53T knock-in lines for fibrillization kinetics. (2) For aggregation biology: preformed-fibril (PFF) seeding in primary neurons or stereotactic mouse injection remains the gold-standard prion-like spread assay; pair with proximity-ligation or split-FP reporters for live oligomer detection. (3) For biomarker work: deploy CSF/skin RT-QuIC as inclusion criterion in any disease-modification trial — clinical-only cohorts are now considered contaminated. (4) For target validation: CRISPRi tiling across the 137 kb locus, including REP1 and distal enhancers, to map causal regulatory variants driving the GWAS signal. (5) For translational readouts: plasma phospho-Ser129 α-synuclein and exosomal species are the leading fluid biomarkers — include in longitudinal sampling.

